==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|never look a gift horse in the mouth}}

===Etymology===
Since horses' teeth grow over time, checking their length is a way of gauging old age, and therefore a sign of mistrust towards the giver.

From {{etyl|enm|en}} texts for “{{l|en|[[given]] [[horse]]}}”:
: ''No man ought to looke a {{l|enm|[[geuen]] [[hors]]}} in the mouth.'' — {{w|John Heywood}}, 1546.
The substitution of ''gift'' for ''given'' occurred in 1663 in {{w|Samuel Butler (poet)|Butler}}'s ''{{w|Hudibras}}'', because the iambic tetrameter required a shortening:
: ''He ne’er consider'd it, as loth''
: ''To look a Gift-horse in the mouth.''
Although uncertain, the origin can be traced even further to {{w|St. Jerome}}'s {{etyl|la|-}} translation {{m|la|equi donati dentes non inspiciuntur}}, from the {{w|Letter to the Ephesians}}, circa AD 400.

